.TH "TEXT\-SAFETY\-SCAN" "1" "January 2020" "helper-scripts" "helper-scripts Manual"

.SH "NAME"
\fBtext\-safety\-scan\fR \- Run all configured text\-safety plugins across files or stdin
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
\fBtext\-safety\-scan\fR [\fB\-\-help\fR] [\fB\-\-\fR] [\fIPATH\fR\|\.\|\.\|\.]
.P
\fBtext\-safety\-scan\fR < \fIinput\fR
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Runs every configured text\-safety plugin (currently \fBunicode\-show\fR(1) and \fBmodeline\-show\fR(1)) against each path argument or against stdin\. All plugins run for every input even if an earlier plugin reports a finding, so a single invocation gives a complete picture\.
.P
This tool intentionally does NOT do directory recursion, MIME classification, VCS pruning, or symlink filtering\. For directory trees, use \fBtext\-safety\-scan\-find\fR(1)\.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR Show usage and exit 0\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-\-\fR End of options\. Remaining arguments are paths\. Required if a path begins with \fB\-\fR\. Plugins handle leading\-dash paths natively (\fBunicode\-show\fR iterates \fBargv\fR then \fBopen()\fR; \fBmodeline\-show\fR forwards via \fBgrep \-\-\fR)\.
.IP "" 0
.SH "EXIT CODES"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB0\fR All plugins clean for all inputs\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB1\fR At least one plugin reported a finding (e\.g\. a Unicode hit or a Vim/Emacs modeline)\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB2\fR Hard error\. Reasons include: an input does not exist, an input is a directory, a plugin is not installed, stdin capture failed, etc\.
.IP "" 0
.SH "EXAMPLES"
Scan a single file:
.IP "" 4
.nf
text\-safety\-scan \./changelog
.fi
.IP "" 0
.P
Scan multiple files explicitly:
.IP "" 4
.nf
text\-safety\-scan \./README \./CHANGELOG \./LICENSE
.fi
.IP "" 0
.P
Scan stdin:
.IP "" 4
.nf
cat \./suspicious\.txt | text\-safety\-scan
curl \-fsSL https://example\.invalid/script\.sh | text\-safety\-scan
.fi
.IP "" 0
.P
Scan a file whose name begins with a hyphen:
.IP "" 4
.nf
text\-safety\-scan \-\- \-\-weird\-name
.fi
.IP "" 0
.P
Scan a tree, using find for the recursion (this is what \fBtext\-safety\-scan\-find\fR(1) does internally):
.IP "" 4
.nf
find /repo \-type f \-print0 | xargs \-0 \-r text\-safety\-scan \-\-
.fi
.IP "" 0
.P
Scan a tree but skip the \fB\.git\fR directory and \fB*\.png\fR images:
.IP "" 4
.nf
find /repo \-not \-path '*/\.git/*' \-not \-name '*\.png' \-type f \-print0 \e
  | xargs \-0 \-r text\-safety\-scan \-\-
.fi
.IP "" 0
.SH "SECURITY MODEL"
\fBtext\-safety\-scan\fR is for AUDITING content, not for hardening against an attacker who can race the scanner\. Specifically:
.IP "\(bu" 4
It is trivial for a scanned file to have malicious text added to it after or even during the scan\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Symlink arguments are followed (\fBopen()\fR follows links by default)\. The user explicitly passed the path; we defer to that\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Semantic text content (such as HTML tags, source code, CI annotations, etc\.) are not sanitized out before being echoed\. However, paths are routed through \fBprintf %q\fR before logging, so they cannot inject control characters or shell special characters into the output\.
.IP "" 0
.P
The intended deployment is: the caller extracts an archive (or checks out a tree) into a directory the attacker cannot write to during the scan, then runs \fBtext\-safety\-scan\fR(1)\.
